modules.description: Generates a buffer containing a specified number of cryptographically secure random bytes, along with an offset indicating the start of the valid data. Works with the bytes type and integer sizes to produce secure byte sequences. Used for creating unique identifiers, encryption keys, or secure tokens in applications requiring randomness.

Generates unique string identifiers using a pseudo-random number generator seeded with the current time. It operates on integer sizes and returns strings of specified length. Used to create short, URL-safe unique identifiers for temporary tokens or session keys.

Generates unique, URL-safe string IDs using a cryptographically secure algorithm, with a configurable length. It operates on byte arrays and strings, producing randomized identifiers based on a custom alphabet. Used to create short, collision-resistant identifiers for URLs, tokens, and unique keys in web applications.

Generates unique random strings using a cryptographically secure algorithm, with a default length of 21 characters. It operates on integer sizes and returns strings formatted as Nano IDs. Used for creating short, unique identifiers in distributed systems or database records.

Generates unique, URL-friendly string IDs using a default alphabet of 64 characters, with a configurable size. It operates on unit input and returns strings suitable for use as identifiers in web applications or data storage. The native implementation uses cryptokit for randomness, making it appropriate for scenarios requiring non-cryptographic uniqueness.
